Vangware curried vanilla aliases.

Collection of curried functional vanilla aliases made entirely in TypeScript. Compatible with all modern JS environments:

  • Node.js.
  • Deno.
  • Browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Edge, and so on).

Usage

This package can be installed as a dependency or used directly.

Usage as ECMAScript module

In JS or deno:

import { map } from "https://cdn.skypack.dev/@vangware/curried?dts";

Or in HTML:

<script type="module" src="https://cdn.skypack.dev/@vangware/curried"></script>

Usage with local installation

First:

npm i @vangware/curried

And then:

import { map } from "@vangware/curried";

CollatorOptions

CollatorOptions: { caseFirst?: CaseFirstFormat; ignorePunctuation?: boolean; localeMatcher?: LocaleMatcher; numeric?: boolean; sensitivity?: SensitivityFormat; usage?: UsageFormat }
  • Defined in types/CollatorOptions.ts:9

Internationalization Collator options.

Type declaration

  • Optional Readonly caseFirst?: CaseFirstFormat

    Whether upper case or lower case should sort first.

  • Optional Readonly ignorePunctuation?: boolean

    Whether punctuation should be ignored.

  • Optional Readonly localeMatcher?: LocaleMatcher

    The locale matching algorithm to use. Default is "best fit".

  • Optional Readonly numeric?: boolean

    Whether numeric collation should be used, such that "1" < "2" < "10".

  • Optional Readonly sensitivity?: SensitivityFormat

    Which differences in the strings should lead to non-zero result values.

    • "accent": Only strings that differ in base letters or accents and other diacritic marks compare as unequal.
    • "base": Only strings that differ in base letters compare as unequal.
    • "case": Only strings that differ in base letters or case compare as unequal.
    • "variant": Strings that differ in base letters, accents and other diacritic marks, or case compare as unequal. Other differences may also be taken into consideration.
  • Optional Readonly usage?: UsageFormat

    Whether the comparison is for sorting or for searching for matching strings. Default is "sort".

    Converts a time to a string by using the current or specified locale.

    example
    const date = createDate("1989-10-13T10:15:31.123Z");
const toLocaleTimeStringGMT = toLocaleTimeString({ timeZone: "GMT" });
const toLocaleTimeStringEnUS = toLocaleTimeStringGMT("en-US");
const toLocaleTimeStringEsAR = toLocaleTimeStringGMT("es-AR");
toLocaleTimeStringEnUS(date); // 3:15:31 AM
toLocaleTimeStringEsAR(date); // 03:15:31
